rook, Gloucestershire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hussey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for someone who habitually wore a distinctive pair of boots or gaiters, from Old French <i>hosed</i>, <i>hoset</i>, <i>housé</i>, Middle English <i>hosey</i>, <i>hus(s)y</i>,‘booted, gaitered’ (from Latin <i>hosatus</i>).","English: status name or nickname from Middle English <i>hus(e)wyf</i> ‘mistress of a family; wife of a householder’ (a compound of Old English <i>hūs</i> ‘house’ + <i>wīf</i> ‘woman’). Though originally a woman's name, it is often found as a male surname, presumably in a derogatory sense. The vocabulary word became <i>hussie</i>, with the meaning ‘disreputable woman’, in the 16th century; the surname, however, is not associated with this meaning.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’. This was the name of a bardic family associated with the Maguires of Fermanagh, also Anglicized as   Oswell   or   Oswald  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hosea","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  . Similarity with the Old Testament prophet's name Hosea (see 3 below) is accidental.","English: in Scotland, where the name is more common, it is sometimes a variant of   Hosie  , itself a form of   Hussey  , or else a variant of   Hossack  .","African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania): from the Biblical personal name <i>Hosea</i>. In the Old Testament, Hosea was a prophet who married a prostitute in order to illustrate Israel's unfaithfulness to God."]},{"name":"Hosie","meanings":["Scottish (northeast Scotland): variant of Irish   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Hassey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Hussey  ."]},{"name":"Oswell","meanings":["English: variant of   Oswald  .","Irish (Ulster): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó hEodhusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Eodhus</i>’ (see   Hussey  )."]},{"name":"Hosey","meanings":["English: variant of   Hussey  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Hussey was born about 1325, in Holbrook, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Sir Reginald Hussey I, Earl of Holbroke, was 36 and his mother, Alinora D'Aubigny, was 26. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Mary Elizabeth De Verdun."},"et":{"about 1325–":"umbes 1325–Surnud","1315–1345":"1315–1345","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1325–1368":"1325–1368","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1334–Female":"1334–Surnud","1327–1400":"1327–1400","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1355–1425":"1355–1425","1290–1338":"1290–1338","1300–1361":"1300–1361","1350":"1350","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1334":"1334","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1453":"1453","07 Mar 1609":"7. märts 1609","1319":"1319","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1328":"1328","Holbrook, Gloucestershire, England":"Holbrook, Gloucestershire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1325–":"noin 1325–Kuollut","1315–1345":"1315–1345","1319–Male":"1319–Kuollut","1325–1368":"1325–1368","1325–Male":"1325–Kuollut","1327–1361":"1327–1361","1334–Female":"1334–Kuollut","1327–1400":"1327–1400","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1355–1425":"1355–1425","1290–1338":"1290–1338","1300–1361":"1300–1361","1350":"1350","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1334":"1334","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","1300":"1300","about 1325":"noin 1325","1453":"1453","07 Mar 1609":"7. maaliskuuta 1609","1319":"1319","about 1350":"noin 1350","1328":"1328","Holbrook, Gloucestershire, England":"Holbrook, Gloucestershire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti,